    <title>Combined summary - Mempool size consensus + dynamic block size re-targetting</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T00:45:39.764703+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-June/009040.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context discusses a proposal for determining the appropriate block size limit for Bitcoin that takes real-time changes to the mempool into account. The proposal involves adding a mempool_size field to each full-node that broadcasts a new transaction, which would allow all nodes to quickly reach consensus on the current average/median/etc mempool size and agree on a suitable periodic blocksize "re-targetting." This approach would enable all full-nodes, not just miners, to vote with their transactions, resulting in truly global consensus. In a discussion, it was pointed out that anyone could lie about the mempool size, but there is no apparent benefit for a full-node to do so, and it is unlikely that the majority of transaction broadcasting full-nodes would engage in such behavior as it goes against their own interests.</summary>
